            <div type="edition" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="grc" resp="#JP" source="http://zotero.org/groups/382445/items/3PK3JKXR">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName type="attested"><name>Ἡράκλειος</name> <name>Διονυσίου</name>
                    <lb n="2"/><name type="demotic">Πετρεῖνος</name></persName> <roleName type="civic" subtype="agoranomos">ἀγορανομέων</roleName>
                    <lb n="3"/>ἐκ τῶν ἰδίων
                </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus" resp="#JP">
                <listApp>
                    <app><note>Text of ISegesta</note></app>
                    <app loc="3"><note>The final Ν is underdotted in I.Segesta, but it is unclear why, as the text is completely clear in the photograph.</note></app>
                </listApp>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" resp="#JP" xml:lang="en">
                <p>Herakleios Petreinos, son of Dionysios, while serving as agoranomos, at his own expense.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="it" source="http://zotero.org/groups/382445/items/3PK3JKXR">
                <p>Herakleios figlio di Dionysios, di Petra, mentre era agoranomos (ha fatto) a sue spese [transl. of I.Segesta]</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>A city of Petra is recorded in Entella A1 = <ref target="http://sicily.classics.ox.ac.uk/inscription/ISic030298">ISic030298</ref>, and so presumably in this region of Sicily; but given that Herakleios holds a magistracy in Segesta, the onomastic element Petreinos is presumably a demotic, and should this refer to the same Petra, the implication is presumably that Petra is now a village of Segesta, or similar.</p>
            </div>
